# Day 3 - Linux Notes

## Input / Output Streams

Linux has three standard input/output streams:

| Stream | Abbreviation | File Descriptor |
|---------|--------------|-----------------|
| Standard Input | stdin | 0 |
| Standard Output | stdout | 1 |
| Standard Error | stderr | 2 |

---

## Input / Output Redirection

### Redirect Output

```bash
command > file
```

Writes output to a file and overwrites existing content.

Example:

```bash
ls > files.txt
```

---

### Append Output

```bash
command >> file
```

Appends output to an existing file.

Example:

```bash
echo "Linux" >> notes.txt
```

---

### Redirect Input

```bash
command < file
```

Example:

```bash
sort < names.txt
```

---

### Redirect Standard Error

```bash
command 2> errors.txt
```

---

### Redirect Both Output and Error

```bash
command > output.txt 2>&1
```

---

## Null Device

```
/dev/null
```

Used to discard unwanted output.

Example:

```bash
ls existing missing > /dev/null 2>&1
```

---

## Comparing Files

### diff

Displays line-by-line differences.

```bash
diff file1 file2
```

### sdiff

Displays differences side-by-side.

```bash
sdiff file1 file2
```

### cmp

Compares files byte by byte.

```bash
cmp file1 file2
```

